<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100032154456215></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100032154456215><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=100032154456215>RE: Snare-Kite</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=100032154456215#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Sep 12th 3:05 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>to kite: snare opponent creature, run away to a distance at which you are out of danger of having your spell interrupted and cast dot, run and dd, run and dd, repeat until enemy creature is dead, re-snare and dot as needed. (if you are kiting any creature with wich you can make use of your animal-fear spells, then replace running with casting fear and chasing behind it and autoattack on, casting dds and dots.) make sure you chose an open area without obstacles to obstruct your casting or aggressive NPCs that will attack you. if you are skilled enough, you can multi-kite with AE spells, but it is not recommended to ameteurs.<br>REMEMBER: druids are NOT a melee class, your melee giving and absorbing abilities arent worth much after lvl20, so bear in mind "Fireballs over fists"<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
